(3, 2, 3, 1, 3, '', 'You often hear the old adage, work smarter not harder. Which to me is liking saying be cunning and not effective or take credit but don’t give effort.<br><div><br></div><div>I don’t see why any logical person wouldn’t choose to do both. In fact that is what you should do, to reach certain heights it’s what you have to do.<br></div><div><br></div><div>Instead of looking at their definitions let’s look at their effects for you, and the perception or the appearance associated<br></div><div><br></div><div>to Work Hard<br></div><div><br></div><div>If you only work harder you get a good end product, better sense of accomplishment, significantly more confidence in what you have done, and you receive much more respect for the work put forth.<br></div><div><br></div><div>to Work Smart<br></div><div><br></div><div>If only working smart then you finish faster, you may use less resources, though the end product isn’t as gratifying, your efforts aren’t seen as something of great value from on lookers. But the good ideas of saving money or time, will be respected by the ones wearing the cufflinks and working really smart, because they’re having you do the work.<br></div><div><br></div><div>To truly be effective you must do them both. Sometimes simultaneously but most of the time. You do them in succession. First you work hard, ALWAYS start with HARD WORK. Hard work is kind of a prerequisite to being able to effectively be a smart worker right? Don’t you have to know what you’re doing to be able to devise a way to do it better?Sadly it is too often people decide to switch from one to the other instead of combining forces. Once you then know the project, duty, job, endeavour, build, process or whatever it is, from top to bottom, and you are the best producer of such; only then should you look for easier ways of completing the tasks at hand (easier and cheaper is the real name for working smarter). To work smart means that with your hard work already put in place, with your understanding and confidence in it all, you can now make sure that you are making better use of resources and time. This would be referred to as efficient.<br></div><div><br></div><div>If you only work hard, then you are the guy that gets hired, never fired but doesn’t even make supervisor. If you only work smart, you’re a great team asset but not team leader, you can earn the label of the guy that is known for taking short cuts, but sometimes known for having good ideas, but never known as an executor.<br></div><div><br></div>If you can work hard and smart. You will be able to lead, create, move forward in groups and independently, see just about everything through to completion, and have the option of running the show if you so choose. She who works hard and works smart, is the one that gets to eventually reap all of the benefits and earns the the opportunity to not have to work at all.', '', '', 1, '2017-05-21 16:52:31', '2017-05-21 16:52:31'),
